Spent the day with the amazing Dr Nickman and Dr Young, and a classroom full of pharmacy students. This is my 6th year speaking to this class and it felt so great to be back in person. This class holds such a special place in my heart and it’s such an honor to give these students a first hand look into the lifetime of medical advancements I have experienced. We have come such a long way since I was diagnosed with cystic fibrosis back in 1980. 

Pharmacists truly make the world go round, they are such an important part of any care team. Dr Young is my life line and I couldn’t be more grateful for all he has done for me over the years. Thank you Dr. Nickman for having us, we look forward to this class every year! Breathe out Love! Xo❤️

🚨BREAKING NEWS!🚨
Today the FDA has approved Trikafta for 2 to 5 year olds in the US. This is HUGE!!! Today we celebrate this amazing milestone!!🎉

I am so excited for my little heroes that will benefit from this amazing drug. We are one step closer… but, we aren’t done yet, and we won’t stop fighting until everyone across the globe has Trikafta or a medication of this magnitude. Breathe out Love! Xo❤️

Today is #NationalSuperHeroDay

When you have CF your body produces a very thick, sticky mucus. So when I tell people my alter ego is Super Mucus Lady. I really am not lying. Throwing it back to 2013 when SML made her first debut… SML is Super Mucus Lady!!

My CF story started today, 43 years ago, just 17 days before my first birthday… May 8, 1980 when my pediatrician called my parents crying to tell them I indeed had CF. Just two days before he assured my mother there was no way I could have had it, since I was such a fat chunky baby, but after seeing a campaign ran by the CFF to kiss your baby she was convinced her very salty tasting daughter had CF. 

My parents were basically told to take me home and love me because I probably wouldn't live to see my 10th birthday. Right then and there my parents chose to fight and fight like hell. They planned a huge 1st birthday party for me and to this day we still celebrate my birthdays as big as we can. 

My parents started the local CFF chapter here in Utah and began doing everything in their power to have me and so many others live a long healthy life. So when I was old enough I adopted my parents philosophy and I joined the fight. In 2001 I started Love To Breathe®️ and began doing everything in my power to raise awareness, educate, and give hope to a community that means the world to me. 

There have been so many breakthroughs that have changed genetic research and led to so many new medical advancements across the board for CF over the years. We have come so far since I was diagnosed in 1980. After every new discovery and medical advancement I can’t help but feel so hopeful. It has solidified my fight and fueled my fire to keep moving forward in hopes that a cure will be right around the corner for everyone with CF. 
⁣
Today we are closer to a cure than we ever have been before, and for the first time in a long time I am filled with more hope than ever. My dream is that with greater lung capacity within our community from these highly effective modulators will come the ability to speak louder for those that still need help. There are still so many in our CF community that don’t have a life saving drug available to them. We aren’t done fighting! I want them to know that I won’t stop, our community won’t stop, the researchers won’t stop. We will keep the momentum going so there will soon be a cure for all! Breathe out Love! Xo💜
#cysticfibrosis #cfawarenessmonth #salty

Perspective is the way we see things when we look at them from a certain distance, and it allows us to appreciate their true value. It’s not always easy to change your perspective, especially when it comes to hard things. CF is one of those hard things. 

CF is inconvenient, CF is exhausting, and CF will never be easy. However, I believe CF has made me stronger, makes me fight harder, love more, and truly appreciate life one breath at a time... CF is a blessing in an ugly disguise, it's my reality and its made me who I am today, and for that I am grateful. Breathe out Love! Xo💜

What is Airway Clearance?!🫁
Airway clearance helps loosen the sticky mucus from the lungs so it can easily be huffed or coughed out. Airway clearance helps Individuals with cystic fibrosis stay healthy and breathe easier. Clearing the airways also reduces lung infections and improves lung function, it is typically done after inhaled medications. 

There are many forms of airway clearance, CPT, Vest, Pep Mask, Active Cycle Breathing, Autogenic Drainage, Aerobika, Flutter, Thera Pep, Acapella and so many more, what works for one person may not work for the other. Every person with CF is so different, and each technique works differently for everyone. As a person with CF gets older they will be able to tell what form of airway clearance will work best for them.

The best forms of airway clearance that work for me are PepMask, which is seen in this photo, combined with "Somergenics" 😉 which is my own technique combining 'Autogenic Drainage' and 'Active Cycle Breathing'. I basically take a variety of breaths at different levels in my lungs that moves the mucus up, so I can easily huff cough it out. I have also used exercise most of my life as part of my airway clearance to help move mucus from my lungs. Breathe out Love! Xo💜
#cysticfibrosis #cfawarenessmonth

Can you imagine having to take pills before you eat anything?! Most people with CF start taking enzymes to help digest food at birth. Can you imagine being a new mom and having to feed your infant applesauce to swallow enzymes…

Cystic Fibrosis doesn't just affect the lungs, just as the lungs produce a thick, sticky mucus, so does the the pancreas. The mucus in the pancreas blocks the release of enzymes needed for digestion. So that's why most people with cystic fibrosis need to take enzymes before they eat. 

When the enzymes are swallowed they go to work in the intestines so you can digest food and absorb the nutrients to keep your body healthy. 

Inside each capsule are many small beads that contain the digestive enzymes. Each bead is covered with a special enteric coating. This coating allows the beads to dissolve in the small intestine where the digestive enzymes are then released to help digest food. Enzymes work for about 45 to 60 minutes after taking them. 

BIG thanks to all my friends who helped me with this post! Pills before every meal... Well I guess you can say we all have our own lil appetizers. Breathe out Love! Xo💜

#cysticfibrosis #cfawarenessmonth

In 1955 most children with CF did not live long enough to attend elementary school.
Fast forward to today… more than half of the CF population are adults.

The 2022 patient registry highlights have been published… I always find them so fascinating, and love being able to see all the highlights in one place. You can download this pdf from cff.org and if you haven’t spent time on the CF Foundation website I highly recommend it. 

I wanted to post the highlights here for anyone who loves looking at CF data. The data is sourced from CF patients who receive care from CFF accredited care centers in the United States. Patients must consent for their data to be included in the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation Patient Registry. Breathe out Love! Xo💜

Today is June 5th 6/5... “65 Roses Day” Have you ever wondered where the term "65 Roses" comes from.... The “65 Roses” story dates back to 1965 when an observant 4-year-old, hearing the name of his disease for the first time, pronounced cystic fibrosis as "65 Roses." Today, “65 Roses” is a term often used by young children with cystic fibrosis to pronounce the name of their disease, since cystic fibrosis can be so difficult to say.

The "65 Roses" story has captured the hearts and emotions of all who have heard it. I had the pleasure of interviewing Richard the boy from this story when he was awarded the Heroes of Hope Award back in May of 2008. You can find the 65 Roses story on CFF.org

The rose, appropriately the ancient symbol of love, has become a symbol of the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation.🌹 Breathe out Love! Xo❤️

10 years ago I loaded Henry up into a jogging stroller and participated in my very first 5k. If you’re new here Henry is my oxygen, and in that stroller was 5 oxygen tanks to help me get past the finish line. 

I did it! It took me over an hour… I love that my one official 5k was for Astra! My friends and I kept repeating the mantra “I’m ok at the 5k”. Scroll to see the magical memory of me crossing that finish line.🎉

HAPPY ROSE UP DAY! 💜
The thing I love the most about Rose Up is that it is inspired by the strength of the cystic fibrosis community. Why we Rose Up is different for all of us, but the one thing that remains the same is that we have ALL come together to help the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation find a cure for ALL. 

Scroll to see the schedule for today and follow along as community members post and go LIVE. Marissa, KC & I will be going LIVE together at 1pm est. I love seeing all the creative ways people are choosing to ROSE UP and more importantly I love hearing your why! Thank you Chad, Lydia, & Andrew, and the amazing Rose Up committee for living that Rose Up lifestyle once again as we celebrate year 4! This community truly is unmatched and inspires me every single day. It’s truly an honor to be apart of it. 

I can’t wait to celebrate with all of you at the Rose Up live event later today at 8 pm est on the Rose Up website. You can still donate to my link below to help further the mission of the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation. Thank you from the bottom of my heart! events.cff.org/ROSEUP/somerlove

“Cystic fibrosis is on the forefront of my mind from the minute I wake up to the minute I go to sleep because it has to be.”

Somer Love knows what it takes to continue showing up with cystic fibrosis. Listen to Somer’s journey growing up with CF, becoming a voice for the community, and finding the strength to continually adapt to each new challenge that presents itself.

Watch the full interview through our site letsrockcf.org in our bio. This Boltcast episode is sponsored by #vertex.

“Finding joy in the mundane and ordinary is truly extraordinary.”
 
Discovering joy in the little things, concentrating on self-wellness, and being a voice of encouragement for the cystic fibrosis community are just a few of the things Somer Love does to adapt and push forward into unknown territory in the world of CF.

Apricity… the warmth of sunlight on a winters day☀️ it’s the lil things that really mean so much to me. I hope to never lose sight of that as we dive into a new year.

A new year can be time for new decisions, hope, gratitude, second chances, changes, and risks. Each day is such a blessing, even the hard days seem to always help us learn and grow. Resetting my mind, body & soul and welcoming 2024 with an open heart and mind. I am taking the month of Jan to reset, refocus, and recharge. Somer Nights season 4 will start Feb 5th. 

Thank you for ALL your love and continued support, Tulip and I appreciate you ALL more than you know. I hope this new year brings you ALL, good health, happiness, lots of love, grace, hope, opportunity, and many magical moments in abundance. Happy 2024 may it be everything and MORE! 
Breathe out Love! Xo❤️
